{
  "A point mutation that changes a single nucleotide and results in a different amino acid in the protein is called a:": "",
  "Frameshift mutation": "",
  "Nonsense mutation": "",
  "Silent mutation": "",
  "Missense mutation": "",
  "A missense mutation is a point mutation where a single nucleotide change results in a codon that specifies a different amino acid. The effect on protein function depends on the chemical properties of the new amino acid and its location in the protein.": "",
  "A nonsense mutation creates a premature stop codon, resulting in:": "",
  "A protein with one different amino acid": "",
  "A truncated (shortened) protein that is usually nonfunctional": "",
  "A longer-than-normal protein": "",
  "No change in the protein": "",
  "A nonsense mutation changes a sense codon into a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA), causing translation to terminate prematurely. The resulting truncated protein is usually nonfunctional because it lacks essential domains.": "",
  "Insertions and deletions of nucleotides that are not multiples of three cause:": "",
  "Frameshift mutations that alter the reading frame of all downstream codons": "",
  "Polyploidy, as conventional deletions theory would suggest": "",
  "Translocations, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Silent mutations according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Frameshift mutations occur when insertions or deletions change the reading frame of the mRNA, altering every amino acid downstream of the mutation. This usually produces a completely nonfunctional protein.": "",
  "A silent mutation does not change the amino acid sequence because:": "",
  "DNA repair mechanisms always fix silent mutations": "",
  "The genetic code is degenerate, so different codons can specify the same amino acid": "",
  "It occurs outside a gene": "",
  "The mutation is in the promoter region": "",
  "The genetic code is degenerate (redundant), meaning most amino acids are encoded by more than one codon. A silent mutation changes a nucleotide but the new codon still codes for the same amino acid, so the protein is unaffected.": "",
  "Chromosomal mutations include all of the following EXCEPT:": "",
  "Translocations": "",
  "Point mutations": "",
  "Inversions": "",
  "Deletions": "",
  "Point mutations involve changes to individual nucleotides and are gene-level mutations. Chromosomal mutations are large-scale changes affecting whole segments of chromosomes and include deletions, duplications, inversions, and translocations.": "",
  "Which type of mutation is most likely to be harmful to an organism?": "",
  "A synonymous substitution": "",
  "Frameshift mutation in the middle of a coding sequence": "",
  "A mutation in a non-coding intron": "",
  "Frameshift mutations in coding regions alter every codon downstream of the insertion or deletion, typically producing a completely nonfunctional protein and often introducing premature stop codons. They are generally the most damaging type of point-level mutation.": "",
  "Genetic variation in sexually reproducing organisms arises from all of the following EXCEPT:": "",
  "Independent assortment of chromosomes": "",
  "Mitotic cell division in somatic cells": "",
  "Crossing over during meiosis": "",
  "Random fertilization": "",
  "Mitosis produces genetically identical daughter cells and does not generate genetic variation. Crossing over, independent assortment, and random fertilization all create new allele combinations, contributing to genetic diversity in populations.": "",
  "A duplication mutation involves:": "",
  "The movement of a segment from one chromosome to another": "",
  "The reversal of a segment within a chromosome": "",
  "The repetition of a segment of a chromosome, resulting in extra copies of genes": "",
  "The loss of a segment of a chromosome": "",
  "Gene duplication creates extra copies of a chromosomal segment. Over evolutionary time, duplicated genes can diverge and acquire new functions (neofunctionalization), making duplication an important source of genetic innovation.": "",
  "Somatic mutations differ from germline mutations in that somatic mutations:": "",
  "Are always lethal in most scenarios involving mutations factors": "",
  "Always affect the entire organism when viewed through a simplified": "",
  "Only occur during meiosis, based on conventional assumptions about": "",
  "Are not passed to offspring because they occur in non-reproductive body cells": "",
  "Somatic mutations occur in body cells (non-gamete cells) and affect only the individual and their descendant cells (e.g., cancer), but are not transmitted to offspring. Germline mutations occur in gamete-producing cells and can be inherited.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a chromosomal inversion?": "",
  "A segment of DNA is duplicated on the same chromosome": "",
  "A segment of a chromosome is reversed in orientation (flipped 180 degrees)": "",
  "An entire extra set of chromosomes is present": "",
  "A segment of DNA is removed from a chromosome": "",
  "A chromosomal inversion occurs when a segment of a chromosome is excised, rotated 180 degrees, and reinserted. The gene order within the inverted segment is reversed, which can affect gene expression and suppress recombination in that region.": "",
  "What is a 'point mutation'?": "",
  "A large-scale rearrangement of a chromosome": "",
  "The loss of an entire chromosome": "",
  "The insertion of an entire gene into a new chromosome": "",
  "A change in a single nucleotide base pair in the DNA sequence": "",
  "A point mutation is the simplest type of mutation, involving the substitution, insertion, or deletion of a single nucleotide in the DNA. Point mutations include transitions (purine to purine), transversions (purine to pyrimidine), and single-base indels.": "",
  "What does 'missense mutation' mean?": "",
  "A mutation that does not change the amino acid sequence": "",
  "A mutation that shifts the reading frame of the mRNA": "",
  "A mutation that creates a premature stop codon": "",
  "A point mutation that changes a codon so that it specifies a different amino acid in the resulting protein": "",
  "A missense mutation is a nucleotide substitution that results in a different amino acid being incorporated into the protein. The impact ranges from benign (conservative substitution) to severe (such as sickle cell disease, where glutamic acid is replaced by valine).": "",
  "What is a 'frameshift mutation'?": "",
  "An insertion or deletion of nucleotides (not in multiples of three) that shifts the translational reading frame, altering all downstream codons": "",
  "A mutation in the promoter that shifts transcription to a new start site": "",
  "The reversal of a chromosomal segment": "",
  "A substitution of one nucleotide for another that changes the reading frame": "",
  "A frameshift mutation occurs when insertions or deletions alter the triplet reading frame of the mRNA. Every codon downstream of the mutation is read differently, usually producing a completely different and nonfunctional amino acid sequence.": "",
  "What does 'translocation' mean in genetics?": "",
  "The movement of ribosomes along mRNA during protein synthesis": "",
  "The migration of DNA polymerase along the template strand": "",
  "A chromosomal mutation in which a segment of one chromosome breaks off and attaches to a non-homologous chromosome": "",
  "The transport of proteins from the cytoplasm to the nucleus": "",
  "A chromosomal translocation involves the transfer of a segment from one chromosome to a non-homologous chromosome. Reciprocal translocations (exchange between two chromosomes) and Robertsonian translocations (fusion of two acrocentric chromosomes) are the major types.": "",
  "What is 'aneuploidy'?": "",
  "A mutation that affects gene expression but not chromosome number": "",
  "A condition in which the chromosome number is not an exact multiple of the haploid number, typically involving the gain or loss of individual chromosomes": "",
  "Having exactly the normal number of chromosomes": "",
  "Having three or more complete sets of chromosomes": "",
  "Aneuploidy refers to having an abnormal number of chromosomes, such as trisomy (2n+1) or monosomy (2n-1). It usually results from nondisjunction during meiosis. Down syndrome (trisomy 21) is the most common viable aneuploidy in humans.": "",
  "What is a 'silent mutation'?": "",
  "A mutation that affects only introns and is always removed during splicing": "",
  "A nucleotide substitution that does not change the amino acid sequence of the protein, due to the redundancy of the genetic code": "",
  "A mutation that silences a gene permanently through methylation": "",
  "A mutation that is never detected by DNA sequencing": "",
  "A silent (synonymous) mutation changes a nucleotide but the new codon still specifies the same amino acid. This is possible because the genetic code has 64 codons but only 20 amino acids, so most amino acids are encoded by multiple codons.": "",
  "What does 'polyploidy' mean?": "",
  "A mutation affecting only a single base pair": "",
  "A condition in which an organism has more than two complete sets of chromosomes (e.g., 3n, 4n)": "",
  "Having an extra copy of a single chromosome": "",
  "Having one fewer chromosome than normal": "",
  "Polyploidy is the condition of having three or more complete sets of chromosomes (e.g., triploid 3n, tetraploid 4n). It is common in plants and is an important mechanism of speciation, as polyploid organisms are often reproductively isolated from their diploid relatives.": "",
  "What is a 'germline mutation'?": "",
  "A mutation that occurs in cells that give rise to gametes (eggs or sperm), so it can be passed to offspring": "",
  "A mutation that only affects the immune system": "",
  "A mutation caused by exposure to germicidal agents": "",
  "A mutation that occurs in somatic cells during an individual's lifetime": "",
  "Germline mutations occur in the germ cells (cells that produce gametes) and are heritable, meaning they can be passed from parent to offspring. These mutations are the basis for inherited genetic diseases and are the raw material for evolution.": "",
  "What does 'genetic variation' mean?": "",
  "The number of genes in an organism's genome": "",
  "The process by which organisms evolve over time": "",
  "The differences in DNA sequences and traits among individuals within a population": "",
  "The total amount of DNA in a cell": "",
  "Genetic variation refers to the diversity of alleles and genotypes within a population. It is generated by mutation, recombination, and sexual reproduction, and is essential for natural selection and adaptive evolution.": "",
  "What is a 'nonsense mutation'?": "",
  "A mutation that has no effect on the organism": "",
  "A mutation that inserts a new start codon into the coding region": "",
  "A mutation that changes one amino acid to a chemically similar one": "",
  "A point mutation that converts a sense codon into a premature stop codon, resulting in a truncated protein": "",
  "A nonsense mutation changes a codon that normally specifies an amino acid into one of the three stop codons (UAA, UAG, UGA). This causes the ribosome to release the incomplete polypeptide prematurely, producing a truncated and usually nonfunctional protein.": "",
  "Sickle cell disease is caused by a single nucleotide substitution in the beta-globin gene (GAG to GTG), changing glutamic acid to valine at position 6. This is classified as what type of mutation, and why is it harmful?": "",
  "A missense mutation that replaces a hydrophilic amino acid with a hydrophobic one, causing hemoglobin to polymerize and red blood cells to sickle": "",
  "A nonsense mutation that truncates the beta-globin protein": "",
  "A silent mutation that has no effect on protein structure": "",
  "A frameshift mutation that shifts all downstream amino acids": "",
  "The sickle cell mutation is a missense mutation where hydrophilic glutamic acid is replaced by hydrophobic valine. This causes the hemoglobin molecules to stick together under low-oxygen conditions, forming stiff polymers that deform red blood cells into a sickle shape.": "",
  "Cystic fibrosis is most commonly caused by a three-nucleotide deletion (delta-F508) that removes a single phenylalanine amino acid from the CFTR protein. Why is this NOT a frameshift mutation, even though it involves a deletion?": "",
  "Because the deletion is in an intron and is spliced out in most scenarios involving deletion factors": "",
  "Because the protein is nonfunctional anyway, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Because deletions can never cause frameshift mutations when considering all relevant deletion factors": "",
  "Because the deletion of exactly three nucleotides removes one codon without shifting the reading frame, so the rest of the protein is translated normally": "",
  "A deletion of three nucleotides (one complete codon) removes one amino acid but does not change the reading frame. All downstream codons are read normally. This is an in-frame deletion, which is less disruptive than a frameshift but still produces a misfolded CFTR protein.": "",
  "A farmer notices that one of his wheat plants has larger seeds and more robust growth than the others. Genetic testing reveals it has four complete sets of chromosomes (4n) instead of the normal two (2n). What term describes this condition, and how might it have arisen?": "",
  "Polyploidy (specifically tetraploidy); it likely arose from a failure of cell division following DNA replication, doubling the entire chromosome set": "",
  "A translocation that moved genes to different chromosomes": "",
  "Aneuploidy; it arose from nondisjunction of a single chromosome": "",
  "A point mutation; a single nucleotide change caused the extra growth": "",
  "Tetraploidy (4n) is a form of polyploidy that can arise from a failure in cytokinesis after DNA replication (endoreduplication) or from fertilization between unreduced (2n) gametes. Polyploidy is common in plants and often produces larger, more vigorous individuals.": "",
  "A researcher discovers that two populations of the same species have very different allele frequencies for a gene controlling color pattern. One population lives in a forest (where dark coloration is advantageous) and the other in a desert (where light coloration is advantageous). Which evolutionary force most likely explains these differences?": "",
  "Gene flow between the two populations": "",
  "Mutation alone": "",
  "Genetic drift in both populations": "",
  "Natural selection favoring different alleles in different environments": "",
  "Natural selection is the most likely explanation: in the forest, dark alleles provide a survival advantage (camouflage), while in the desert, light alleles are favored. Over time, selection increases the frequency of advantageous alleles in each environment.": "",
  "The Philadelphia chromosome, found in chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML), is caused by a reciprocal translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22 that creates the BCR-ABL fusion gene. How does this chromosomal mutation lead to cancer?": "",
  "It deletes a tumor suppressor gene on chromosome 22": "",
  "The translocation prevents DNA replication in bone marrow cells": "",
  "The fusion gene encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase that drives uncontrolled cell proliferation": "",
  "It duplicates the entire genome, leading to polyploidy in blood cells": "",
  "The translocation fuses the BCR gene on chromosome 22 with the ABL kinase gene on chromosome 9, creating a chimeric BCR-ABL protein that is a constitutively active tyrosine kinase. This kinase continuously signals cell proliferation, causing leukemia.": "",
  "A conservation biologist studies two populations of cheetahs and finds that both have very low genetic variation. DNA analysis reveals that all cheetahs are nearly genetically identical. What is the most likely historical explanation for this low genetic diversity?": "",
  "Cheetahs have an extremely high mutation rate that eliminates variation": "",
  "Cheetahs experienced a severe population bottleneck that drastically reduced genetic variation, and the species has not yet recovered": "",
  "Natural selection has made all cheetahs perfectly adapted, eliminating all variation": "",
  "Cheetahs reproduce asexually, preventing genetic recombination": "",
  "Cheetahs experienced one or more severe population bottlenecks (dramatic reductions in population size) that eliminated most genetic variation through genetic drift. The surviving small population carried only a fraction of the original diversity, and the species has remained genetically depauperate.": "",
  "Gene duplication events have been important in evolution because duplicated genes can:": "",
  "Accumulate mutations freely since one copy maintains the original function, potentially evolving new functions (neofunctionalization)": "",
  "Immediately create a new species through reproductive isolation": "",
  "Only produce identical proteins, providing no evolutionary advantage": "",
  "Only undergo deletions, never gaining new functions": "",
  "Gene duplication provides raw material for evolution. One copy continues to perform its original function, while the other copy is free to accumulate mutations. This can lead to neofunctionalization (new function), subfunctionalization (dividing original functions), or pseudogenization (loss of function).": "",
  "A mutation in a regulatory region upstream of a gene increases the gene's expression tenfold. Even though the protein's amino acid sequence is unchanged, the organism shows a dramatically different phenotype. What does this demonstrate about the nature of mutations?": "",
  "This must be an example of epigenetic inheritance, not mutation": "",
  "Only mutations within coding regions can affect phenotype": "",
  "Mutations in regulatory regions can significantly alter phenotype by changing when, where, or how much a gene is expressed, without changing the protein itself": "",
  "Regulatory mutations are always silent and have no effect": "",
  "Regulatory mutations can have profound phenotypic effects by altering gene expression levels, timing, or tissue specificity. Many evolutionary changes between species are attributed to mutations in regulatory regions (enhancers, promoters) rather than changes in protein-coding sequences.": "",
  "A population geneticist compares the DNA sequences of a gene in two related species and finds that the rate of synonymous (silent) substitutions is much higher than the rate of nonsynonymous (amino acid-changing) substitutions. What does this pattern suggest about the gene?": "",
  "The gene is under purifying (negative) selection, which removes most amino acid changes because they are harmful": "",
  "The gene is not under any selective pressure": "",
  "The gene has been recently duplicated in both species": "",
  "The gene is under positive selection, rapidly evolving new functions": "",
  "When synonymous substitutions exceed nonsynonymous substitutions (dN/dS < 1), it indicates purifying selection: most amino acid changes are deleterious and are removed by natural selection, while silent changes accumulate neutrally. This pattern is seen in highly conserved, functionally important genes.": "",
  "A student asks: 'If mutations are random and mostly harmful, how can they be the source of all genetic variation that drives evolution?' Which response best addresses this question?": "",
  "Organisms can direct their mutations toward beneficial changes in response to environmental needs": "",
  "Most mutations are actually beneficial, so they directly improve organisms": "",
  "Mutations are not actually random; they occur preferentially in genes that need improvement": "",
  "While most mutations are neutral or harmful, the rare beneficial mutations are preserved and accumulated by natural selection over many generations, gradually building adaptive variation": "",
  "Mutations are indeed random and mostly neutral or harmful. However, across large populations and long time periods, the occasional beneficial mutation provides a selective advantage. Natural selection preserves these rare beneficial variants, and over generations, they accumulate, driving adaptive evolution.": ""
